					</div>

					<p>What we don’t know is if his coaches will have the same trust in exposing him to the seam area of the field where bang-bang plays and unseen hits are the norm.  The temptation will be strong, as the seam is where Gronk has done so much damage in his career…both to other teams’ defenses, and now unfortunately, to his own knee.  Gronk may feel ready, but are the play-callers?    

					<p>Gronk isn’t helped in this whole situation by a league that’s directed players down to the lower (unprotected) parts of offensive players’ bodies, to avoid hitting areas having the most protective equipment.  For safety.  That makes a whole thimble-full of good sense. 
					 
					<p>My guess is that for Sunday, we may see Gronk major more in low crossing routes, curls, outs, and isolated situations outside the numbers where boundary throws are less likely to draw contact from an unseen charging safety. 
					 
					<p>But that’s just a guess. 
					 
					<p>What we do know with relative certainty is the NFL’s best tight end will be back on the field Sunday, playing the game he loves.  And the NFL is better for it. 
